Author: dukeleto#7326
Content: @AkiraX it depends on the situation, and different branches of math like to define it differently. 0^0=1 is what C language `pow` returns https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero_to_the_power_of_zero

Author: dukeleto#7326
Content: some people care more about 0^x, where x goes to 0. others care more about x^0, where x goes to 0. The first function is equal to 0 for all x>0, while the second is equal to 1 for all x>0. So whether you define 0^0 as 0 or 1 depends on which function you would like to be continuous/differentiable at zero ğŸ˜ƒ

Author: dukeleto#7326
Content: "there is only one way to order zero elements" => 0^0=1, while "zero times itself any number of times is zero" => 0^0=0
